Part 1 - Introduction 👩‍⚕️¶

In this project, I am going to analyze health insurance company data to predict future claims and identify factors that influence healthcare costs. The main objective of this project will be the premise for determining the cost of the company's health insurance product. I identified two major research questions that needed to be addressed, namely:

  • On what factors do the annual hospital fees paid by health insurance depend, and how do they impact?
  • Which predictive model gives the best results?

Dataset information¶

Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/teertha/ushealthinsurancedataset

"US Health Insurance Dataset" is a public dataset on Kaggle, which can be helpful in a simple yet illuminating study in understanding the risk underwriting in Health Insurance, the interplay of various attributes of the insured and see how they affect the insurance premium.

Therefore, it can be state that age has a great influence on the payment of hospital fees.

The obese group pays the most for medical expenses, the median charges of the obese group are close to 10,000 but their average is more than 15,000, which shows that in the data of the obese group there are many outliers that can much larger value than the general average of this group data. This is also the group that gathers many major exceptions to the entire group of charges. The underweight group had the lowest medical costs, and the mean and median of the group differed by about 3,000 on the mean side, also suggesting that there are outliers on the larger side as well. In the boxplot chart, this group only has 1 outlier.

The number of obese and overweight people accounts for most of the upper bound of the charges group. However, the obese group is also at the lower end of the charges group, which can be conjectured to be due to the concern for their own health or the income of this group of people.

<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x2ac4601c7c0>

Figure 1:

  • The line showing the influence between (age + children) on charges is a linear, covariate winning line.
  • The line with the highest slope: group 1 children (orange) -> age affects the charges of people in group 1 children is the strongest
  • The line with the smallest slope: group of 4 children (purple) -> age affects the charges of people in group 4 children is weakest
  • As the charge value is higher, the distribution becomes more sparse in all five groups

Figure 2:

  • The line showing the influence between (bmi + children) on charges is a linear, covariable winning line except for the group with 5 children (probably due to unequal data sets)
  • The line with the highest slope: group 2 children (banana green) -> BMI has the strongest impact on charges of people in group 1 children
  • The line with the smallest slope: the group of 5 children (brown) -> BMI has the weakest impact on the charges of those in the group of 5 children
  • As the charge value is higher, the distribution becomes more sparse in all five groups

Part 3 - Create model 📈¶

In [66]:
def removeOutliers(df, column):
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    return df[(df[column] > lower) & (df[column] < upper)]

Part 4: Conclusion 🎯¶

In this project, I performed exploratory data analysis to better understand the dataset and how features might be associated with charges. After that, I used linear regression method to predict the Insurance charges. It can be clearly seen that model 2 is the best for all indicators including RMSE, MAE, R^2, Adjusted R^2.

In fact, this dataset is quite easy for machine learning models to classify. However, my purpose of doing this project is to learn how to mine data by exploring each feature, select features for my model, and perform machine learning models.

I hope you enjoy this project. If you have any questions, please feel free to contact me. Thanks for reading!
